  "slug": "paneer-tikka-masala",
  "title": "Paneer tikka masala",
  "subtitle": "Grilled paneer cubes in tomato and cream sauce",
  "excerpt": "Paneer cubes marinated in spiced yoghurt and char-grilled until the surface chars, then simmered in the same tomato, cream, and butter sauce as chicken tikka masala. The paneer holds its texture in the sauce where chicken would soften, the contrast between the slightly firm, charred exterior and the smooth, rich sauce is the dish's defining quality. The vegetarian answer to chicken tikka masala.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Paneer tikka masala is the vegetarian parallel to chicken tikka masala, applying the same tikka-and-masala-sauce structure to grilled paneer. It has been on British Indian menus since the 1980s and is consistently the most popular vegetarian main for non-vegetarian diners.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Paneer behaves differently from chicken in the tikka stage. It doesn't absorb marinade in the same way, the marinade coats the surface rather than penetrating the interior. This means the char on the outside is more important for paneer than for chicken: the charred, spiced surface is the main flavour contribution the tikka stage makes, and it must be properly dark and caramelised to have impact in the finished sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The sauce is the chicken tikka masala sauce with no modifications. Use the same formula: caramelised onion base, tomatoes reduced to a paste, butter, cream, and fenugreek leaves. The paneer goes in at the end, just long enough to warm through. It should not braise in the sauce for more than 5 minutes, or it will become rubbery.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
