      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Marinate and grill the paneer",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the {{plain-yoghurt}}, {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{garam-masala}}, {{chilli-powder}}, {{turmeric}}, {{vegetable-oil}}, and a pinch of salt. Add the {{paneer}} cubes and turn to coat. Leave for at least 1 hour. Preheat a cast-iron griddle pan until smoking. Grill the paneer for 2 to 3 minutes per side until well charred in spots. Remove and set aside.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{unsalted-butter}} in a wide pan over medium heat. Add the {{onion}} and cook for 10 minutes until golden. Add the {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{cumin-ground}}, and {{coriander-ground}} and stir for 1 minute. Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}} and cook for 10 minutes until reduced to a thick paste. Add 100 ml water and simmer for 5 minutes. Stir in the {{double-cream}} and {{fenugreek-leaves}}. Season with salt. Add the grilled paneer and warm through on low heat for 3 to 4 minutes. Serve immediately.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add paneer to the finished sauce off the heat, or on the very lowest setting. It needs only to warm through, not to cook further",
              "cause": "Kept too long in the hot sauce",
              "symptom": "Paneer rubbery in the sauce"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Wipe excess marinade from the paneer before grilling, a thick layer prevents direct contact with the pan. The griddle must be smoking",
              "cause": "Pan not hot enough or too much marinade left on",
              "symptom": "Paneer doesn't char on the griddle"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The sauces are the same. The textural contrast (firm paneer vs. chicken) and the charred paneer flavour are what differentiate the dish",
              "cause": "It is the same sauce, the difference is in the paneer",
              "symptom": "Sauce tastes identical to chicken tikka masala"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cut paneer into 3 cm cubes minimum. If using very fresh soft paneer, press between two plates for 30 minutes before cutting to firm it",
              "cause": "Cut too small or fresh paneer not firm enough",
              "symptom": "Paneer falls apart on the griddle"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Paneer tikka masala is the curry-house main for people who want tikka masala without the chicken. It sits on the menu next to saag paneer. Both are veggie mains, but they pull in different ways. Saag paneer leans on spinach and cream. This one leans on a rich, spiced sauce and the smoke from charred paneer. The char carries into the sauce in a way that plain fried paneer does not.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
